ned academic with appointments at Duke, Stanford, Emory, and Singularity Universities, draws on his new Kauffman Foundation research to show that the United States is in the midst of an unprecedented halt in high-growth, immigrant-founded start-ups. He argues that increased competition from countries like China and India and US immigration policies are leaving some of the most educated and talented entrepreneurial immigrants with no choice but to take their innovation elsewhere. The consequences to our economy are dire; our multi-trillion dollar loss will be the gain of our global competitors.With his signature fearlessness and clarity, Wadhwa offers a concise framework for understanding the Immigrant Exodus and offers a recipe for reversal and rapid recovery.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aBusinesspeople. 0aEntrepreneurship-United States. 0aEntrepreneurship. 0aForeign workers-Government policy-United States. 0aSuccess in business. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Entrepreneurship.2bisacsh  aSilicon Valley entrepreneurship.  aUS immigration policies.  acountry caps.  aentrepreneurial immigrants.  aentrepreneurs.  aglobal competitors.  agreen cards.  aimmigration.  ainnovation.  astart-ups.  avisas.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/9781613630204?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781613630204423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781613630204/original  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles 